It IS taking place there is no doubt about it, due to human pollution. Since 1900 sea levels have risen between 10 25cm, this is not much I must admit, but very much higher then over the past several THOUSAND years. Our Ice caps are melting fast and swallowing up the lowlands. Global warming is causing many more extreme weather paterns then we would have seen 100 years ago, floods, droughts, gales... in 1998 (the hottest year on record) enviromental refugees outnumbered (for the first time) those displaced by war. 58% of the worlds refugees were fleeing natrual disasters. These are just off the top of my head. Believe me the list could go on, and on.... and on.<br>
<br>
&quot; - should we act upon it, to preserve the climate for future generations, or should we let nature take its course and just learn to adapt?&quot;<br>
Let nature take its course? If it wasn't for us, and our attitudes, maybe yes, Nature could take its course. In the past evolution has let us adapt (and survive) but the changes are happening to fast, evolution can't keep up with the changes we are making. And its not just us who are taking the battering, speices are dying out faster then ever... They simply CAN'T adapt, and neither can we.<br>
 <br>
&quot;If you're a personal hedonic egoist, then fuck future generations, all that matters is what makes you happiest right now.&quot;<br>
Yes that is the attitude of most politicians. We can make a difference, every little helps.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do you feel it is immoral to perhaps not care or act, or are you quite content to live out your own lifespan(and perhaps your childrens) and thats all that you care about?&quot;<br>
Yes I care, we cannot be so short sighted, and turn a blind eye to the sufferings of our future counterparts.<br>
<br>
finally a quote. &quot;We do not inherit the planet from our parents, we borrow it from our children&quot; Think about it.<br>
<br>
Swallow.<br>
